'''Thomas "Tommy Gun" Oosthuizen''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|w|ɛ|s|t|.|h|aɪ|z|ɨ|n}} {{respell|WEST|hy-zən}})<ref>[http://www.waggleroom.com/2010/7/16/1573143/how-to-properly-pronounce-louis]</ref> is a [[South African people|South African]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]] and the current [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] [[Super Middleweight]] champion.<ref name="boxer">[http://boxrec.com/media/index.php?title=Human:460738 Thomas Oosthuizen - BoxRec Boxing Encyclopaedia] ''BoxRec''. Retrieved on 2011-09-16.</ref> ''[[Ring Magazine|The Ring Magazine]]'' presently ranks him at fourth in the [[Super Middleweight]] division, while [[ESPN.com|ESPN]] has him at number nine.<ref name="rating1">{{cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/ratings/supermiddleweight |title=The Ring Ratings, Super Middleweight| publisher= ''The Ring''|accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref><ref name="rating2">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=6995567 |title=ESPN.com's divisional rankings| publisher= ''ESPN''|accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref> He is managed and trained by Harold Volbrecht whilst being jointly promoted by both [[Lou DiBella]] and [[Golden Gloves Ltd]].<ref name="info">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldengloves.co.za/fighter/thomas-oosthuizen/ |title=Thomas "Tommy Gun" Oosthuizen - Golden Gloves| publisher= ''Golden Gloves''|accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref>

==Family==

Thomas is the son of former two-division South African champion Charles Oosthuizen.<ref name="boxer"/>

==Professional career==

Oosthuizen made his professional debut on 29 February 2008, knocking out Johannes Swart in two rounds. He then reeled off twelve straight victories, nine of which coming by way of knockout.<ref name="record"/>

===IBO super middleweight title===

On 6 November 2010, Oosthuizen faced off against [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] [[Super Middleweight]] titleholder [[Isaac Chilemba]]. The result was a split-decision draw which allowed Chilemba to retain the title, Oosthuizen claims that attempts to make a rematch were swiftly declined.<ref name="interview">{{cite web | last =Wainwright|first =Anson| title =Thomas Oosthuizen: "I will take an ugly win over a pretty loss any day."  | work = | publisher =''Max Boxing'' | date =20 September 2011 | url= http://www.maxboxing.com/news/promo-lead/thomas-oosthuizen-i-will-take-an-ugly-win-over-a-pretty-loss-any-day | accessdate =2011-09-28}}</ref> On 26 March 2011, Oosthuizen got a second crack at the [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] title against Evert Bravo (Chilemba had vacated the title to move up to the [[Light Heavyweight]] weight class).<ref>{{cite web | last =Jackson|first =Ron| title =Oosthuizen-Bravo for IBO belt   | work = | publisher =''Fightnews'' | date =3 September 2011 | url= http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/oosthuizen-bravo-for-ibo-belt-79204 | accessdate =2011-09-28}}</ref> Oosthuizen won the fight via a ninth round technical knockout, which saw the referee stepping in to save Bravo from taking further punishment.<ref>{{cite web | last =Chaykovsky|first =Edward| title =Thomas Oosthuizen Stops Evert Bravo, Wins IBO Title   | work = | publisher =''Boxing Scene'' | date =26 March 2011 | url= http://www.boxingscene.com/thomas-oosthuizen-stops-evert-bravo-wins-ibo-title--37459 | accessdate =2011-09-28}}</ref> Oosthuizen made his American debut on the undercard of the [[Jan Zaveck vs. Andre Berto]] bout, winning a unanimous decision over Aaron Pryor Jr on 3 September 2011.<ref>{{cite web | last =Chaykovsky|first =Edward| title=Oosthuiszen, Bailey and Del Valle Win Bouts in Biloxi  | work = | publisher =''Boxing Scene'' | date =3 September 2011 | url= http://www.boxingscene.com/oosthuiszen-bailey-del-valle-win-bouts-biloxi--43353 | accessdate =2011-09-28}}</ref>

